Fin. 

And kuddos to anyone who caught that “Aint i soft ?” is me also mocking the fact that a white woman wrote that shit.

BW cannot (as a collective) say “I am sick[ly]. I am weathered. I need care.” because despite y’all pretending to be shocked about disdain for disabled people, we all know deep down there is contempt for sick[ly] folk. So instead we’re getting “Aint i soft?”.

People gender softness but these oppressive ways of being strip us all of the ability to actually be soft for fear of proximity to weakness. &Fear of proximity to weakness is fear of proximity to disability (& other embodied vulnerabilities like childhood🙃).
Surviving as a BW forces you to abandon parts of yourself central to your humanity.

Or it forces you to bury any parts of yourself that are soft despite what personality type you are. 

This is a point the FP girls bring up in a very clumsy anti-black way... They  make it about femininity but this isn’t about femininity. It’s about humanity.

Also... a lot of the desires to be (engaged as) soft aren’t just about aspiring to be a damsel. Surviving [cis hetero, yt supremacist, capitalist] patriarchy  FORCES you to NOT be soft even if you are indeed soft.
Fragile as in a yt supremacist, classist/ capitalist, ableist, anti black & anti indigenous fragility tied up in white women’s gender construct.

It’s a farce of course as even yt womanhood was not actually constructed this way in real life.

But the ideology persists. The only women who get “taken cared of” are fragile women. Not fragile as in disabled or weathered. Those women are to be disposed of.
The only thing left is to lean into something that already exists despite it not actually fully being accessible to us and that is gendered* fragility.

We’re at a point we’re lots are rejecting the violence of the demand to be & perform “strong”. 

But we’re not yet at the point where it is acceptable to embrace the politics of disability because ableism...

Though many of these women are likely to have conditions that qualify them as disabled (bodily & socially) because black folk have higher rates of disability, they are very unlikely to think of themselves through that  lens.
But what language is there to discuss fragility if you are not connected to the black disabled community?

& no matter your location,  if you are black and woman then you’re more likely to be weathered than not. 
I had no choice but to face my physical condition (fragility) as a kid, but other BW are being smacked in the face w the reality of their fragility.

As someone who has been severely chronically ill & disabled their entire life, I had to face the harsh realities of mortality & ability and aging long before I had my first period. “Avg” people don’t contend with that until middle aged. 
But we* are black...

This had nothing to do with the misogynoirist conditioning black girls encounter about being strong. My mother initially was hoping to raise a lady (evangelical expectations aka yt fem/respectability). Instead she got me. A hurricane.
I was and always will be a rebel child. Stubborn/ strong willed. Pugnacious. Fiery. The women i aspired to be like when I was a kid  were not the damsels. They weren’t soft or docile.

Fragile as in genetically. 
Fragile as in weathered (hold on to this.) 
Not fragile as in colonial/euro farce about [yt] womanhood. 

Any time I touch on it with a close friend,  I always speak about how my bodily realities are at odds with my personality.

So I had one of those “I’m tired” venting moments with a friend and I was talking about how I had to accept at a very young age how (physically & ultimately psychiatrically) fragile I am. 

I am intentional with the use of the word fragile as a disabled BW.

When their social conditions don’t improve. 
No meds or counseling can shield you from the daily retraumatizing of surviving these conditions. 

So many people are tired. It’s truly disheartening.

People are sick and tired (literally) and there’s so few resources that are truly helpful because as a tweeter I RTd earlier already said, how can people’s mental health improve when their material conditions don’t improve?

Most people cite these spaces as traumatizing spaces. As someone who has worked in MHC including institutions, is completing edu to be an MH practitioner, as someone hoping to contribute to decolonizing psych, I see those spaces as often inflicting more harm.

It really upsets me that even if the answer would one day be “yes” that I still wouldn’t want to go because of how violent those institutions are. I’ve interned at such institutions. I have loved ones who have been.

I’ve found myself asking myself multiple times in the last year “do I need to be checked into inpatient psychiatric care?” 

I know the answer is still no  but the fact that I’ve asked myself at least 6 times is really difficult for me.

Meds have made intrusive/impulsive thoughts disappear/stay contained but I’m scared that one day the dam will break & biology will win. 
I’m not scared of not being here. I just don’t want to leave in a manner that wasn’t within my control.

But I’m realizing day by day that I am subconsciously hoping that it will be enough to prevent me from unaliving myself since I can’t find the energy to do anything else. 

I’m terrified that one day my logical brain will shut off.

So during the pandemic I find myself only able to “distract” myself by obsessing over my physical needs. Sleep. Hygiene. Eating. Movement. 

At first I said “I’m just taking care of my most  urgent needs!”

And that scares me. It scares me in the wake of my aunt’s death. 

A death my family refuses to accept for what it is.

I used to be able to distract myself with projects and academe and social work & all these other things but nothing works anymore. I simply cannot find the ability to care about anything enough to be distracted from my mental health issues.

There are many, many days when I find myself asking if I’m really going to have spend the rest of my life feeling the way I do because it’s getting increasingly more difficult to find reasons to live even though I have no intention of dying any time soon.

Scared because though I’ve made great progress physiologically on meds, I don’t really think they’ve done that much for my psychological health. I understand my family history & that I’m just genetically on the severe side of the MH spectrum.

I’m gonna be honest. The news of Regina’s son & now Cheslie has been really triggering for me. 
In the last few months, I’ve found myself thinking about my aunt almost every day because I’m a bit scared.
